President Biden has declared a major disaster in the State of Minnesota due to severe storms and flooding that occurred from April 11 to April 30, 2023. This declaration allows for Federal assistance to supplement state, tribal, and local recovery efforts in the affected areas. Federal funding will be provided to governments and certain nonprofit organizations on a cost-sharing basis for emergency work and the repair or replacement of damaged facilities. The counties included in this declaration are Aitkin, Big Stone, Carlton, Chippewa, Clay, Grant, Houston, Kittson, Lac qui Parle, Lake of the Woods, Mahnomen, Marshall, Morrison, Norman, Pine, Pope, Renville, Roseau, St. Louis, Stevens, Swift, Traverse, and Wilkin, as well as the Prairie Island Indian Community. Hazard mitigation measures statewide will also be eligible for cost-sharing funding. Mr. Joseph P. Cirone of FEMA will coordinate Federal recovery operations in the affected areas, and additional designations may be made in the future based on further damage assessments. For more information, media can contact the FEMA News Desk.